# Skill Integration Rules for XiHong ERP

This repository is skill-first. Skills define the default workflow. Project rules only add repository-specific constraints.

## Priority Chain

```
user instructions
> repository-specific constraints (.cursorrules)
> superpowers + planning-with-files
> other skills
> archived OpenSpec material
```

## Core Interpretation

- Use `superpowers` as the default workflow engine.
- Use `planning-with-files` for complex multi-step work.
- Use `.cursorrules` only for stack-specific and safety-specific exceptions.
- Treat `openspec/` as archive-only reference material.
- For collection authoring conversations, prefer the already-loaded PowerShell `pwcli` helper commands when they exist in the active shell profile, instead of reintroducing manual setup or longer fallback wrappers.
- For Dashboard architecture work, prefer the PostgreSQL path:
  - `semantic` for standardization
  - `mart` for reusable aggregates
  - `api` for page-module query views
- Treat PostgreSQL Dashboard cutover as the active direction for the Dashboard query path.
## Skill Mapping

### brainstorming (superpowers)

- Use it for new features, rule redesigns, behavior changes, and architecture discussions.
- Default design-doc location in this repository is `docs/superpowers/specs/`.
- Do not redirect brainstorming output into OpenSpec.

### writing-plans / executing-plans (superpowers)

- Default plan-doc location is `docs/superpowers/plans/`.
- Use `writing-plans` when you want a durable implementation plan document.
- Use `executing-plans` only when there is already a written plan to execute.

### planning-with-files

- Allowed and recommended for complex single-person work.
- `task_plan.md`, `findings.md`, and `progress.md` intentionally live in project root.
- These files are gitignored and do not violate repository rules.
- Do not combine `planning-with-files` with OpenSpec in this repository.

### test-driven-development (superpowers)

- Fits naturally with Contract-First.
- Preferred order:
  - define contract
  - write failing test
  - implement minimal code
  - verify

### webapp-testing

- Standalone scripts and test utilities may use sync Playwright.
- Backend runtime code must stay async-first and use `async_playwright`.

### frontend-design + ui-ux-pro-max

- Adapt all design output to Vue 3 + Element Plus + Pinia + Vite.
- Ignore React and React Native implementation advice.
- Reuse existing frontend architecture instead of introducing a new component system.

### systematic-debugging / code-review / verification skills

- Use them directly. No extra workflow override is needed.

## Decision Quick Reference

```
"I need to build or redesign something"
  -> brainstorming
  -> writing-plans or planning-with-files
  -> test-driven-development

"I need to fix a bug"
  -> systematic-debugging
  -> test-driven-development
  -> verification-before-completion

"I need to do a complex refactor or research task"
  -> planning-with-files

"I need to design a page or component"
  -> ui-ux-pro-max + frontend-design
  -> implement in Vue 3 + Element Plus

"I need browser automation"
  -> webapp-testing
```

## OpenSpec Status

- Keep `openspec/` in the repository as history.
- Do not create new OpenSpec proposals or route active work through OpenSpec unless the user explicitly asks for historical lookup or migration work.
